definitions: of, relating to, or resembling cats in appearance or behavior
having the smooth, graceful movements typical of cats
examples: The zoo has a new feline exhibit with lions and tigers
Her feline features included almond-shaped eyes and high cheekbones
The dancer moved with feline grace across the stage
His feline reflexes helped him catch the falling vase

definitions: fierce, cruel, or terrible in nature or appearance
relating to hills or upland areas, especially barren rocky land
examples: The dragon swooped down with fell intent to destroy
In one fell swoop, the storm destroyed the entire harvest
They hiked across the fell landscape of northern moors
The fell country stretched for miles without a single tree

definitions: having qualities or appearance traditionally associated with women or girls
denoting a gender of nouns and adjectives in certain languages
examples: She wore a feminine dress with delicate lace details
The room had a feminine touch with soft colors and flowers
In Spanish, the word 'casa' takes the feminine article 'la'
French feminine adjectives often end with an extra 'e'

definitions: advocating for women's rights and equality between the sexes
examples: She joined the feminist movement to fight for equal pay
The university offers several feminist literature courses

definitions: existing in a wild state, especially after escape from domestication
examples: The island has a population of feral cats living in colonies
His feral eyes darted around the room looking for escape routes

definitions: covered with or resembling ferns in appearance or texture
examples: The ferny undergrowth made walking through the forest difficult
She decorated the room with ferny plants in hanging baskets

definitions: savagely fierce, cruel, or violent in manner or appearance
examples: The ferocious storm destroyed hundreds of homes along the coast
The team played with ferocious intensity throughout the championship game

definitions: containing or relating to iron, especially with valence two
examples: The soil had high ferrous content making it red in color
Ferrous metals are attracted to magnets unlike non-ferrous ones

definitions: producing or capable of producing abundant vegetation or crops
able to conceive young or produce seed
examples: The fertile valley produced enough food for the entire region
After the floods, the soil became more fertile than before
The doctor confirmed that both partners were fertile and healthy
Rabbits are extremely fertile animals with frequent litters

definitions: having or displaying passionate intensity of feeling or belief
examples: She was a fervent supporter of environmental protection causes
His fervent prayers could be heard throughout the chapel

definitions: cheerfully celebratory, relating to or suitable for a festival
examples: The house looked festive with colorful lights and decorations
Everyone was in a festive mood at the holiday party

definitions: relating to or characteristic of a fetus in the womb
examples: The ultrasound showed normal fetal development at twenty weeks
She curled into a fetal position to protect herself

definitions: attractive or appealing in appearance, especially in a charming way
examples: She looked quite fetching in her new summer dress
The cottage had a fetching view of the mountain lake

definitions: relating to feudalism or the medieval system of land ownership and loyalty
examples: The feudal system dominated European society for centuries
Some feudal customs persisted long after the Middle Ages ended

definitions: having or showing symptoms of fever with elevated body temperature
displaying nervous excitement or energy in excessive amounts
examples: The child felt feverish and needed to stay home from school
Her feverish skin was hot to the touch
They worked at a feverish pace to meet the deadline
The crowd reached a feverish pitch of excitement

definitions: the smallest number or amount possible, superlative of few
examples: This route has the fewest traffic lights to downtown
Of all the teams, they made the fewest mistakes

definitions: having supernatural powers or appearing touched by magic or fate
examples: She had a fey quality that made people think she could see the future
The forest had a fey atmosphere in the moonlight

definitions: containing, consisting of, or resembling fibers in structure
examples: Celery has a fibrous texture that some people dislike
The fibrous roots spread deep into the soil

definitions: changing frequently, especially regarding loyalties, interests, or affection
examples: The fickle weather changed from sunny to stormy within hours
Her fickle nature made it hard to maintain friendships

definitions: relating to or occurring in fiction; invented for literature
examples: Sherlock Holmes is a fictional detective created by Conan Doyle
The movie was based on fictional events during wartime

definitions: not real or true; imaginary or fabricated deliberately
examples: He gave a fictitious name when checking into the hotel
The company was sued for making fictitious claims about their product

definitions: created by the imagination rather than based on reality
examples: The author's fictive world included dragons and magic
Poetry often employs fictive elements to express deeper truths

definitions: annoyingly trivial or petty in nature or amount
examples: They wasted time on fiddling details instead of big issues
The fiddling amount wasn't worth arguing about

definitions: involving trust, especially regarding the relationship between trustee and beneficiary
examples: The lawyer had a fiduciary duty to protect client interests
Banks have fiduciary responsibilities to their account holders

definitions: having or displaying an intense or ferocious aggressiveness
showing a heartfelt and powerful intensity
examples: The fierce lion protected her cubs from danger
The two armies engaged in fierce combat
She felt fierce loyalty to her hometown team
The competition was fierce among the top students

definitions: consisting of fire or burning strongly and brightly
having a passionate, quick-tempered nature
examples: The fiery sunset painted the sky orange and red
They escaped the fiery inferno just in time
Her fiery speech inspired the crowd to action
He had a fiery temper that flared up quickly

definitions: equivalent to the sum of ten and five; one more than fourteen
examples: There were fifteen students in the advanced math class
The recipe calls for fifteen minutes of baking time

definitions: constituting number fifteen in a sequence; coming after fourteenth
examples: Her fifteenth birthday party was a memorable celebration
The fifteenth amendment granted voting rights regardless of race

definitions: constituting number five in a sequence; coming after fourth
examples: She finished fifth in the marathon despite her injury
The fifth grade students went on a field trip

definitions: constituting number fifty in a sequence; coming after forty-ninth
examples: They celebrated their fiftieth wedding anniversary with family
The fiftieth state to join the union was Hawaii

definitions: equivalent to the product of five and ten; half of one hundred
examples: The speed limit on this road is fifty miles per hour
She invited fifty guests to her retirement party

definitions: relating to or consisting of human or animal figures in art
examples: The figural sculptures in the museum date from ancient Greece
Her figural paintings capture the human form beautifully

definitions: departing from literal use of words; metaphorical rather than actual
examples: The phrase 'break a leg' has a figurative meaning of good luck
Poetry often uses figurative language to create imagery

definitions: decorated with a design or pattern rather than plain
examples: She wore a figured silk scarf with paisley designs
The figured wallpaper added visual interest to the room

definitions: relating to or due from a son or daughter to parents
examples: His filial devotion led him to care for aging parents
Filial piety is highly valued in many Asian cultures

definitions: containing as much or as many as possible; having no empty space
examples: The filled stadium erupted with cheers when the team scored
Her schedule was filled with back-to-back meetings

definitions: covered with a thin layer or coating of something
recorded on film or video camera for viewing
examples: Her filmed eyes showed she had been crying recently
The windows were filmed with condensation from the steam
The filmed documentary won several prestigious awards
The entire ceremony was filmed for television broadcast

definitions: extremely dirty, unpleasant, or morally offensive in nature
examples: The abandoned house had filthy floors covered in debris
His filthy language shocked everyone at the formal dinner

definitions: of superior quality, skill, or appearance compared to others
consisting of smaller particles or having thinner consistency
examples: This restaurant serves finer cuisine than the one downtown
She had finer taste in art than most collectors
The finer sand felt softer between their toes
Use a finer grade of sandpaper for the final polish

definitions: having fingers of a specified kind or number mentioned
examples: The three-fingered sloth moves slowly through the trees
She wore fingered gloves that allowed better dexterity

definitions: brought to an end or completed with nothing more to do
having a smooth, polished, or refined surface or manner
examples: The finished project exceeded all client expectations
Are you finished with your homework yet?
The table had a beautifully finished mahogany surface
Her finished performance showed years of training

definitions: having limits or bounds; not infinite in size or extent
examples: Earth's natural resources are finite and must be conserved
There's only a finite amount of time to complete this task

definitions: dismissed from employment, typically for cause or downsizing
hardened or colored by heat in a kiln or furnace
examples: The fired employees received severance packages from the company
He was fired for consistently arriving late to work
The fired pottery had a beautiful glazed finish
These bricks were fired at extremely high temperatures

definitions: able to resist fire or great heat without burning or damage
examples: The fireproof safe protected important documents from the blaze
They installed fireproof insulation throughout the building

definitions: denoting the first child born to particular parents
examples: Their firstborn daughter inherited the family business
Many cultures give special privileges to the firstborn child

definitions: coming from the original source or personal experience directly
examples: She had firsthand knowledge of the situation from being there
Travelers shared firsthand accounts of their adventures

definitions: tasting, smelling, or resembling fish in some way
arousing doubt or suspicion; seemingly dishonest
examples: The fishy smell from the kitchen meant dinner was ready
This salmon tastes too fishy for my preference
Something seems fishy about his explanation for being late
The deal looked fishy so we decided not to invest

definitions: capable of being split or divided, especially along natural planes
examples: Uranium-235 is a fissile material used in nuclear reactors
The fissile rock layers split easily along their grain

definitions: made or shaped to fit a particular person or thing precisely
examples: She wore a fitted dress that showed her figure perfectly
The fitted sheets stayed secure on the mattress all night

definitions: in better physical condition or health than something being compared
examples: After months of training, she was fitter than ever before
The fitter candidates passed the physical examination easily
